The Governor of Central Bank of Nigeria, Godwin Emefiele, has said that the bank is still insisting on the repayment of loans borrowed by the states, adding that bank will commence deducting the loans. Emefiele also stated that the commercial banks have written to the central bank and the Ministry of Finance, Budget and National Planning requesting for the repayment of loans owed. He disclosed this while responding to interview questions at the end of the two-day monetary policy committee meeting held in Abuja on Tuesday. He said, “On the CBN intervention facility to the state government we are engaging in the national economic council and the CBN is also insisting on its loans to be paid but the outcome of the engagement between central bank finance and national economic council we will begin to take the monies. “I am aware that the banks have written to the finance and they have copied me, that they want their money. I am not part of it so they should pay their loans.” He encouraged the states to repay the loans to ensure future assistance from the banks. “In any case it is good for you to be a good debtor; if you take a loan from a bank, you pay, so that when you go back to the bank, you can get.” The PUNCH had reported that state governors requested that the repayment of support loans borrowed from the CBN, which ought to start this month, be deferred. Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com